00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:06.239
would give us the time of day. uh there

00:03:03.599 --> 00:03:10.480
was that point like why would you ever

00:03:06.239 --> 00:03:12.080
need ML to to write code. Um at the same

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:14.319
time I think that we totally

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:16.959
underestimated how fast this could go.

00:03:14.319 --> 00:03:20.239
When we did that project originally the

00:03:16.959 --> 00:03:22.800
idea was to look at how we could speed

00:03:20.239 --> 00:03:24.720
up the evolution of a piece of code. How

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:27.280
could we make many of those small

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:29.599
changes which slows down code speed

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:31.599
development? you know the small edit

00:03:29.599 --> 00:03:33.440
which requires a review that takes three

00:03:31.599 --> 00:03:35.040
days and how we could compress that

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:36.879
cycle.

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:39.360
Some people were talking about vibe

00:03:36.879 --> 00:03:41.280
coding writing code in English and at

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.879
the time honestly I totally dismissed

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:44.959
that. I was that's why we have

00:03:42.879 --> 00:03:47.840
programming language. English is not a

00:03:44.959 --> 00:03:51.040
programming language. Well I I guess I

00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:53.360
was pretty wrong on that front. But the

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:56.239
resistance we felt at the time reminded

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:59.360
me of how my own career was pretty

00:03:56.239 --> 00:04:01.840
resistive to to change. Um I've been

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:05.360
writing code for

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:08.799
45 years. Uh I started by writing video

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:10.959
game for Apple 2 and Commodore 64. So uh

00:04:08.799 --> 00:04:14.239
my formation was to write assembly

00:04:10.959 --> 00:04:16.160
language. And when you spend a long time

00:04:14.239 --> 00:04:18.400
writing assembly language, you look at

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:20.160
compilers with a lot of suspicion,

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:22.320
right? are those things really working

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:24.800
correctly? And then when you switch to

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:28.160
C++ and use compiler, you lose you look

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:30.000
at garbage collected languages as this h

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:32.880
that's not real programming. You need to

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.840
manage your memory. Well, today I use

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:39.520
Python and V coding. So even old dogs

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:43.040
can learn new tricks. So uh but I I I do

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:45.919
understand what happened there.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:48.160
I think that we have a number of eras in

00:04:45.919 --> 00:04:50.560
what happened with software and and the

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:52.800
first one was you know the one where I

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:55.919
started writing code where the

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:58.479
fundamental limit was really the machine

00:04:55.919 --> 00:05:01.759
and there was a lot of work to go and

00:04:58.479 --> 00:05:05.680
extract the last ounce of power out of

00:05:01.759 --> 00:05:08.000
those machine and that was the days of

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:09.759
assembly language where you really

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.560
needed to be incredibly accurate in the

00:05:09.759 --> 00:05:14.639
way you were writing code computing

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:18.000
became much cheaper and we switched to

00:05:14.639 --> 00:05:19.600
the modern cloud era where getting the

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.240
best performance is not the most

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:25.759
critical aspect. You can actually brute

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:28.479
force many problems but really what

00:05:25.759 --> 00:05:31.520
became the limiting factor was the

00:05:28.479 --> 00:05:33.759
ability for us to design in a modular

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:36.960
way. You know this was the era where

00:05:33.759 --> 00:05:38.639
software was write it only once and this

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:41.440
was this whole idea of how are you going

00:05:38.639 --> 00:05:43.520
to build libraries? How are you going to

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:45.199
write functions? How are you going to

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:47.759
break down that problem into something

00:05:45.199 --> 00:05:50.320
that is long-term manageable?

00:05:47.759 --> 00:05:52.320
The limitation there and that determine

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:55.280
a lot of how our software process are

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:58.560
working where actually the human brain.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:01.600
Uh a traditional human typical human is

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:04.479
able to get the context between seven

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:06.639
and nine tokens. I mean we have very

00:06:04.479 --> 00:06:09.199
rich tokens but you compare that to

00:06:06.639 --> 00:06:12.400
modern ML where the context is basically

00:06:09.199 --> 00:06:14.319
going to be infinite pretty soon. uh

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:16.560
that fundamental limitation of human

00:06:14.319 --> 00:06:19.840
determined a lot of how software was

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:23.360
being written. This is over and we're

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:25.120
switching now to that AI frontier where

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.440
really writing the code is not the

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:29.199
challenge anymore. Uh I'll speak some

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:32.000
more about it. But the bottlenecks are

00:06:29.199 --> 00:06:33.919
really how do you ensure that that code

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.840
is what you really wanted because

00:06:33.919 --> 00:06:38.160
writing the code is easy but getting

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:41.440
what is needed for a specific problem

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:43.919
can be much harder to to specify.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:46.560
So humans at least in the near future

00:06:43.919 --> 00:06:47.919
will be that role of architecture or

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:50.240
thinking of what are really the

00:06:47.919 --> 00:06:53.759
implication of that piece of code. I'm

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:55.759
getting the ML to to design. Inductive

00:06:53.759 --> 00:06:58.240
thinking is another category where I

00:06:55.759 --> 00:07:01.520
think humans still have a very clear

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:03.520
edge which is to look at a system in a

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:05.680
much wider context and to be able to

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:08.880
detect patterns and from those pattern

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:12.400
take some decision.

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:15.039
So where are we today? Um, superhuman

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:17.680
syntax generation.

00:07:15.039 --> 00:07:19.919
When is the last time I got Gemini to

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:21.840
write a function for me? And I looked at

00:07:19.919 --> 00:07:23.680
the function and I was like, I can do

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:26.479
that better.

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:28.319
It's over. Uh, I think that the minutia

00:07:26.479 --> 00:07:29.919
of code writing, I mean, you can fight,

00:07:28.319 --> 00:07:34.160
you can argue, you can find counter

00:07:29.919 --> 00:07:36.319
example, but that time is is gone. Where

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:39.599
we still have a lot of work to do is

00:07:36.319 --> 00:07:42.479
multi-step code base. Uh software

00:07:39.599 --> 00:07:44.960
engineering is not about writing code.

00:07:42.479 --> 00:07:47.360
Software engineering is the first time

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:50.479
you join a company and you realize that

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:52.319
there are 35 million lines of PHP in the

00:07:50.479 --> 00:07:54.319
codebase and that you need to make some

00:07:52.319 --> 00:07:56.160
changes. That that's the day you

00:07:54.319 --> 00:07:58.720
understand what software engineering is

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:00.160
and that's a place where our models

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:02.720
today or frontier models are

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:05.280
progressing. But this ability to manage

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:07.919
that extreme complexity and break it

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:09.440
down into man manageable pieces is a

00:08:07.919 --> 00:08:11.280
place where the frontier is still

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:15.440
moving.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:17.759
Um it goes all the way to architecture.

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:19.280
You look at I don't know the Google

00:08:17.759 --> 00:08:21.440
architecture.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:23.919
Thanks God we have Jeff Dean which was

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:25.840
you know the the key architect there.

00:08:23.919 --> 00:08:28.240
But that's the level of thinking which

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:30.400
has many implication which can go from

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:32.800
how do you do hardware optimization? How

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:35.120
do you manage security? How do you build

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:37.680
a system so that 10 years later you're

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:40.479
not full of regrets? And I think this is

00:08:37.680 --> 00:08:43.360
really the the range of progress we are

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:45.279
working on today. So code is over but

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:48.080
there's plenty to do. There's plenty of

00:08:45.279 --> 00:08:51.440
progress to be made.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:53.279
Now code is a very unique problem and in

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:57.440
some way that's the reason we we did

00:08:53.279 --> 00:09:00.399
pitchfork on this. Um,

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:01.920
first of all, code is a lot of data.

00:09:00.399 --> 00:09:03.920
There are other domains where you can

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:06.160
find a lot of data to train your model,

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:09.040
but code was so incredible. You could go

00:09:06.160 --> 00:09:11.279
and go on GitHub and start to to scrape

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:12.959
GitHub. So, this was one of those

00:09:11.279 --> 00:09:16.480
problem where the amount of training

00:09:12.959 --> 00:09:18.240
data was a very unique situation.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:21.519
It is also a domain where doing

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:23.440
verification is reasonable. You can run

00:09:21.519 --> 00:09:26.240
a piece of code, you can compile it, you

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:28.240
can have unit test. So the ability to

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:30.720
figure out is the model generating

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:33.920
something correct was something that was

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:36.399
pretty reasonable to do. That brought us

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:38.320
where we are today. But today what

00:09:36.399 --> 00:09:42.000
happened is that we run out of training

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:44.399
data. I think that 80% of the new code

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.440
added to GitHub today is machine

00:09:44.399 --> 00:09:49.920
generated. So the notion of human

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:52.320
bringing some knowledge that can be used

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:55.040
for mining and to train model is

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:58.320
reaching an end. But the good news is

00:09:55.040 --> 00:10:00.320
that we can do selfplay and selfplay is

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:03.440
something we always liked a lot at deep

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:06.399
mind. I suppose all know Alpha Zero.

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:09.600
Alpha Zero became a superhuman go and

00:10:06.399 --> 00:10:12.959
chess player without any human knowledge

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:15.760
just by playing against itself. We are

00:10:12.959 --> 00:10:18.240
now at that stage where Frontier model

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:20.240
for code are able to do the same where

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:22.240
they can create their own challenge.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:24.720
They can judge the validity of the

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:27.760
answer. they can even to some extent

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:30.480
judge the architecture. So that ability

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:33.279
to do those hundreds of millions of

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:35.040
hours of selfplay writing code is the

00:10:33.279 --> 00:10:37.040
thing that will bring us to the to the

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:38.640
next layer. You know, it's interesting.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:40.560
Um

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:42.959
do the experiment. Take a a brilliant

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:45.279
software engineer, lock him in a room,

00:10:42.959 --> 00:10:48.480
lock him or her in a room for two years

00:10:45.279 --> 00:10:49.760
and feed pizza and give the mission you

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:52.320
need to become a better software

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:54.240
engineer. What do you do as a person?

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:56.560
you you give yourself some challenges,

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:58.240
challenges that you can verify and you

00:10:56.560 --> 00:11:01.040
keep working and coding on those

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:03.519
challenges. We can do the same here. So

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:06.480
this is an issue of how much compute,

00:11:03.519 --> 00:11:08.800
how much selfplay time we can have. But

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:13.160
that will bring the horizon of how far

00:11:08.800 --> 00:11:13.160
we go in superhuman coding.

00:11:13.519 --> 00:11:18.160
So the economics of code are changing

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:20.079
dramatically. You know, as I say, we

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:22.640
developed a whole software engineering

00:11:20.079 --> 00:11:25.120
culture and infrastructure and set of

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:27.040
companies based on the assumption that

00:11:25.120 --> 00:11:29.680
writing code was the hard part. That

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:32.880
this was the expensive part. We're now

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:34.800
in a world where writing code is free or

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:37.600
nearly free. That's why I've got the

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:39.920
tilda there.

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:42.160
That means that the amount of code that

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:44.240
we're going to see produced is going to

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:46.800
explode. And there are some hard

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:49.920
implications to that. First is the

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:51.839
question of design and adequacy. How in

00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:54.320
front of that mountain of code which

00:11:51.839 --> 00:11:56.640
will be written or written dynamically,

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:59.279
how do we keep systems which works and

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:01.760
are reliable at the microscopic level?

00:11:59.279 --> 00:12:05.360
Great role for human.

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:07.600
It is also the issue that you know we're

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:09.920
writing code and we're not reading it

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:12.399
very much anymore. I mean I know we

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:14.800
still have code review but I would

00:12:12.399 --> 00:12:17.040
predict that in one year we'll let

00:12:14.800 --> 00:12:20.160
Gemini or other model generate the code

00:12:17.040 --> 00:12:22.480
and nobody will actually look at it. You

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:24.480
know it's similar to compilers who still

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:29.440
check the assembly output of their

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:31.360
compiler and maybe someone there but

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:33.279
that's probably the end of it. So the

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:35.040
same thing is going to happen to code

00:12:33.279 --> 00:12:37.120
and that brings some question of what

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:40.000
are the new process that we need to put

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:41.773
in place to keep that manageable

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.639
and that's where I've got a

00:12:41.773 --> 00:12:47.360
[clears throat] a bit of a list active

00:12:44.639 --> 00:12:50.160
guard rails. I mean you've all seen the

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:53.519
news of mythos looking at a piece of

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:57.120
code and detecting a unreasonable number

00:12:53.519 --> 00:12:59.440
of vulnerability in that code.

00:12:57.120 --> 00:13:02.000
there is a rush to go and patch those

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:04.639
vulnerability but I think that's going

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.560
to be a neverending process you know

00:13:04.639 --> 00:13:10.000
we're going to get a certain layer of

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:12.079
vulnerability discovered by models we're

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.320
going to fix those models will get

00:13:12.079 --> 00:13:17.360
smarter they will go a bit deeper and

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:19.040
find even more subtle vulnerability so I

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:21.839
think that the first aspect is that we

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:24.639
need to think at least as much about

00:13:21.839 --> 00:13:26.880
code security and the implication of a

00:13:24.639 --> 00:13:29.360
piece of code than on the code writing

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:31.839
itself and the grail and you know

